<paragraph pageId="397" pageNumber="398">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="397" pageNumber="398" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hageni">Bembidium hageni</taxonomicName>
Hayward, 1897: 89. Replacement name for 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="397" pageNumber="398" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexpunctatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="397" pageNumber="398">Bembidium sexpunctatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(LeConte, 1852). Etymology. The specific name honors Herman August Hagen [1817-1893], physician, entomologist, and bibliographer. Born in East Prussia, Hagen moved to Cambridge in Massachusetts at the age of 50 on the insistence of Louis Agassiz and worked at the Museum of Comparative Zoology. He eventually became professor of entomology at the University. His impressive library was bought by the MCZ.
</paragraph>
